"Written evidence submitted by Refugee Action (JRR 0001)&#xa0;\n-\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \ninterve\nned\n in the case of \nMK &amp; AH v Secretary of State for the Home Department [2012] EWHC 1896 (Admin\n)\n \nwhich \nfound that the failure of the Home Office to provide access to support for asylum seekers waiting for a decision on their further claim for asylum for a minimum of three weeks \nled\n to homelessness and destitution.\n-\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \ncommenced legal proceedings against the Ho\nme Office to challenge the level of financial support paid to people seeking asylum. The essence of \nthis judicial review\n is that the amount paid to destitute individuals and families (including those with children) is unlawful because it is insufficient to\n meet their essential living needs or to provide a dignified standard of living.\n \n              \nThe role of judicial review\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n              \nEvidence\nEvidence about the s\nignificant growth\n of judicial reviews:\n \nEvidence about \na\nbuse by campaigning organisations: \nPublic messaging\n-\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \n‘Jud\nicial reviews are brought by groups who seek nothing more than cheap headlines’ (paragraph 3\n of the consultation document\n)\n-\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nJudicial review ‘\nis not a promotional tool for countless Left-wing campaigners\n […]\n \nBritain cannot afford to allow a culture of Left-w\ning-dominated, single-issue activism to hold back our country from investing in infrastructure and new sources of energy and from bringing down the cost of our welfare state.\n’\nLegal aid context\nPaying for permission to work in judicial review cases\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\n&#xa0;\nInterventions\nNovember 2013\n6\n&#xa0; Alongside our Home Office-funded reactive advice services, we have substantial experien